english:
  title: A Memorial Requesting the Abolition of Private Military Forces
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I, an official of the Censorate, along with my colleagues from the Secretariat, humbly submit the following petition:

    Military authority is the great instrument of state power. It must have unified command; it cannot be scattered among many hands. When military power becomes fragmented without central control, it is like placing a sword's hilt into another's grasp—impossible to wield with restraint. When many hold command of armies, each builds factions and gangs of followers. Their hearts divide, their interests splinter. They grow suspicious of one another and sow seeds of rebellion and ruin. Brothers turn against brothers, and meritorious servants find no security. This plague has afflicted every age, both ancient and modern.

    Confucius taught: "In ancient times, households kept no weapons in their halls"—meaning there existed no private armies. The Book of Rites records: "To store weapons and armor in a private dwelling violates propriety. This amounts to threatening the sovereign." When ministers possess private armies, they inevitably grow overreaching and menace their lord.

    The sages established laws and left us warnings to shield posterity from such calamities. How perfect their foresight! When the Song Emperor Taizu assumed the throne, through calm discourse and gentle persuasion, he dissolved the military powers of his generals, allowing them to live in peace and security—a model for all ages to follow. The Three Families of Lu, the Six Ministers of Jin, the warlords who rose at the Han's decline, the military governors who ran rampant in Tang's twilight—all nurtured private armies to fuel their rebellions. Let these be warnings to us.

    When our Former King founded this realm, he established the Three Armies Bureau with exclusive command over military power—a grand and far-sighted design. Yet advisors of that time argued that, being the dawn of a new age with hearts still unsettled, we must guard against unforeseen upheavals. Thus they counseled that royal kinsmen and merit subjects each maintain private forces to meet emergencies. By this reasoning, private armies were never fully abolished. Yet those who held such forces became the very architects of rebellion—disaster struck without warning. Only through Heaven's blessing did the Prince pacify the turmoil and restore order to the realm, bringing us to this present day.

    Still, the question of private armies remains unresolved, custom persisting where reform should prevail. The Censorate has already memorialized requesting their abolition. Yet Your Highness, trusting in the loyalty of royal kinsmen and merit subjects, allowed them to maintain such forces. Not long after, calamity erupted among those closest to the throne itself. This proves that private armies bring only chaos and yield no benefit—the Censorate's words have proven true. Yet these private forces remain unabolished, and the dangers that may come are deeply troubling.

    Moreover, in the provinces, military forces are scattered among various commanders. Some serve as palace guards, others as auxiliary units, and private retinues burden the people with endless rotations and requisitions. The abuses abound. Attendant companies grow bloated, hunting expeditions multiply endlessly. Soldiers and horses go hungry and weary, exposed to wind and snow, standing night watch at private gates. Discontent swells among the people—a situation most lamentable. Of all the great evils afflicting our realm today, none exceeds this.

    I humbly petition that henceforth all provincial commanders stationed in the capital be dissolved. Let all military forces, from the capital and provinces alike, be placed under the Three Armies Bureau, constituting the realm's public army. Thus establish unified command, strengthen the sovereign's authority, and gather the people's hearts. Apart from guards at the two palaces, prohibit all private household watches. When officials journey to court, let no armed retainers attend them. By this, we honor the ancient principle: "In ancient times, households kept no weapons in their halls." We forestall the beginnings of future discord and conspiracy. This would be a blessing for our realm.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Three Armies Bureau (義興三軍府) was established during the founding of Joseon Dynasty to centralize military command.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'calamity among the closest' refers to the Prince's own struggle with royal kinsmen over succession and power.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'two palaces' (兩殿) refers to the residences of the current ruler and the former ruler.
  - key: ''
    value: This memorial was submitted during a period of political tension regarding military authority and the power of noble families in early Joseon.
